With the Indian Child Welfare Act under assault by the right as never before, I want to be on the front lines of all these fights, serving my country as the next Rep. for #NY24.

NY has never had an Indigenous member of Congress, it would be my great honor to be the first. /End

I have never lost that desire to serve this country I love, but this time my goal is to serve as a member of Congress.

Because while abortion rights and environmental justice are on the ballot this year, so is tribal sovereignty. /8

This sense of service to the homeland was a value instilled in me as the son of Indigenous parents. It's no accident that Native Americans enlist in the U.S. military at 5x the national average.

But that sense of service did not end when I left the U.S. Army. /7

As we know, the US has a history of taking Indigenous children off tribal lands and placing them with white families, as they did with my mom. My father, who is of Ottawa heritage, was told to sign away his land. He refused.

Yet I signed up to fight in the U.S. Army. /6

I was lucky to be raised on a dairy farm and now live in the pristine Lake District of NY. Protecting these lands is not just a mission of mine, it's a deeply ingrained legacy.

My opponent has been clear she wants to bring fracking back to New York State.

Not on my watch. /5

That's why the radical Dobbs decision and conservative abortion bans offend me to my core. 

And why I believe so strongly that reproductive rights are human rights and have pledged to codify Roe when I am elected to Congress. /4

This is a value passed down through generations of Native cultures, so many of which had women as their leaders.

For me, the right to control your own reproductive choices is about human dignity and being able to control your own destiny. /3

As a child I was raised mostly by my mom, who was of Cherokee heritage. She was adopted off a reservation when she was 3 years old.

She ingrained in me a deep belief and trust in women, not just as leaders but as people with sovereignty over their own lives, bodies & choices. /2

Today, on #IndigenousPeoplesDay, I am reflecting on my own Indigenous heritage and how it informs my public service to this day.
